Run:

```shell
ASAN_OPTIONS=detect_leaks=1:halt_on_error=0 \
LSAN_OPTIONS=report_objects=1 \
./ssls_import_leak
```

LeakSanitizer reports:

```text
==1383615==ERROR: LeakSanitizer: detected memory leaks

Direct leak of 524416 byte(s) in 128 object(s) allocated from:
    #0 0x0000004a6f98 in malloc (/omitted/curl-master/ssls_import_leak+0x4a6f98) (BuildId: d8f7c4dc12985f17896846f2707c00052f903097)
    #1 0x7f526dd85a9f in curlx_memdup0 /omitted/curl-master/lib/curlx/strdup.c:87:37
    #2 0x7f526dd80bfc in spack_decdata16 /omitted/curl-master/lib/vtls/vtls_spack.c:179:10
    #3 0x7f526dd80bfc in Curl_ssl_session_unpack /omitted/curl-master/lib/vtls/vtls_spack.c:298:16
    #4 0x7f526dd7ccd0 in Curl_ssl_session_import /omitted/curl-master/lib/vtls/vtls_scache.c:1193:12
    #5 0x7f526dc61fe1 in curl_easy_ssls_import /omitted/curl-master/lib/easy.c:1350:10
    #6 0x000000400a96 in main /omitted/curl-master/ssls_import_leak.c:177:14
    #7 0x7f526d8f3680 in __libc_start_call_main (/lib64/libc.so.6+0x3680) (BuildId: 18472003bbf1c5f098a09b5016b9b8bd4c7c59f0)
    #8 0x7f526d8f3797 in __libc_start_main@GLIBC_2.2.5 (/lib64/libc.so.6+0x3797) (BuildId: 18472003bbf1c5f098a09b5016b9b8bd4c7c59f0)
    #9 0x000000400ee4 in _start (/omitted/curl-master/ssls_import_leak+0x400ee4) (BuildId: d8f7c4dc12985f17896846f2707c00052f903097)
```

`524416` is `128 * 4097`. Each import leaks the first 4096-byte ticket allocation plus the extra terminating byte allocated by `curlx_memdup0()`.

The relevant code is:

```c
case CURL_SPACK_TICKET:
  result = spack_decdata16(&pval8, &s->sdata_len, &buf, end);
  s->sdata = pval8;
  break;
```

When another `CURL_SPACK_TICKET` field is encountered, `s->sdata` is overwritten without freeing the allocation associated with the previous field.

### I expected the following

Malformed serialized session data containing duplicate ticket fields should either be rejected or handled without losing the previous allocation.

### curl/libcurl version

curl master (87704c4)

### operating system

Fedora Linux 44
7.0.12-201.fc44.x86_64 #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu Jun 11 01:30:16 UTC 2026 x86_64 GNU/Linux

## Description

Between curl 8.19.0 and 8.21.0, `curl_multi_socket_action` leaks sockets (they end up stuck in `CLOSE_WAIT`, never `close()`d) when a single multi handle talks to many distinct hosts under a small `CURLMOPT_MAXCONNECTS`. It reproduces deterministically and is **not** related to `Connection: close` handling — it reproduces just as strongly against 100% keep-alive-capable servers.

Isolated with a minimal C reproducer (attached below) against a controlled Alpine Linux 3.24.1 base with **only the `curl`/`libcurl` package version swapped** (8.19.0-r0 vs 8.21.0-r0, both from Alpine's own apk repos) — everything else (Alpine base, musl, OpenSSL, kernel, container) held identical.

## Reproduction results

| libcurl | hosts | MAXCONNECTS | requests | CLOSE_WAIT leaked |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 8.19.0 | 16 (all keep-alive) | 5 | 3000 | 2 (noise) |
| **8.21.0** | 16 (all keep-alive) | 5 | 3000 | **~1015 (~34%)** |
| 8.21.0 | 16 (all keep-alive) | 1000 (no eviction pressure) | 3000 | 1 (noise) |
| 8.19.0 | 16 (2 sending `Connection: close`) | 5 | 3000 | 2 (noise) |
| **8.21.0** | 16 (2 sending `Connection: close`) | 5 | 3000 | **~1015 (~34%)** |

Leak magnitude is essentially identical whether or not any host sends `Connection: close` — the trigger is purely **connection-cache eviction pressure** (small `MAXCONNECTS` relative to the number of distinct hosts in flight), not response header handling. Removing the eviction pressure (large `MAXCONNECTS`) makes the leak disappear entirely on 8.21.0. 8.19.0 never leaks under any tested condition.

## Steps to reproduce

1. Build the attached `repro.c` with `gcc -O2 -o repro repro.c -lcurl` against libcurl 8.19.0 in one environment and 8.21.0 in another (identical OS/base otherwise — e.g. Alpine 3.24 with the `curl-dev` package version-pinned via `--repository` to Alpine's v3.23 apk repo for the 8.19.0 side).
2. Run N (e.g. 16) local HTTPS servers on `127.0.0.1:19100..19115` (self-signed cert, `SSL_VERIFYPEER`/`SSL_VERIFYHOST` off in the client) — any subset can send `Connection: close`, it does not affect the result.
3. Run: `./repro https://127.0.0.1: 16 <n_close_hosts, e.g. 0> 20 3000 5`
   (base_url, n_hosts, close_host_count, concurrency, total_requests, `CURLMOPT_MAXCONNECTS`)
4. After it finishes and enters its inspection sleep, check the process's sockets: `ss -tn state close-wait` (or `/proc/<pid>/fd`).
5. Expected: near-zero `CLOSE_WAIT` sockets. Actual on 8.21.0: hundreds, growing proportionally with total requests, spread across the keep-alive hosts (not concentrated on the `Connection: close` ones).

## Source-level analysis (not yet runtime-verified with a debugger — offered as a starting point, not a confirmed root cause)

Diffing `lib/conncache.c` and `lib/cshutdn.c` between the two tags turned up two changes that plausibly combine to cause this:

1. **The `do_close` filter-type callback was removed entirely** (`struct Curl_cftype` in `cfilters.h` no longer has a `do_close` field). The old `Curl_conn_close()` (called `cft->do_close()` on just the top filter, leaving structures allocated) was replaced everywhere by `Curl_conn_cf_discard_all()` → `Curl_conn_cf_discard_chain()`, which iterates the whole filter chain calling `.destroy()` on each filter and freeing it immediately. This is the only non-cosmetic change in `cshutdn.c`'s `Curl_cshutdn_terminate()`:
   ```c
   -  Curl_conn_close(admin, SECONDARYSOCKET);
   -  Curl_conn_close(admin, FIRSTSOCKET);
   +  Curl_conn_cf_discard_all(admin, conn, SECONDARYSOCKET);
   +  Curl_conn_cf_discard_all(admin, conn, FIRSTSOCKET);
   ```
   In isolation this looks safe (`cf_socket_destroy()` in `cf-socket.c` does call `socket_close()` when `ctx->sock != CURL_SOCKET_BAD`), but it changes what happens when this path fires **while a filter (e.g. TLS) is mid-graceful-shutdown**.

2. **The async graceful-shutdown queue shares its capacity with the live connection pool's `CURLMOPT_MAXCONNECTS`.** In `Curl_cshutdn_add()` (`lib/cshutdn.c`):
   ```c
   size_t max_total = cshutdn->multi->max_total_connections;
   if(max_total > 0 &&
      (max_total <= (conns_in_pool + Curl_llist_count(&cshutdn->list)))) {
     cshutdn_destroy_oldest(cshutdn, data, NULL);  /* force-terminates the oldest shutdown-queue entry */
   }
   ```
   With a small `MAXCONNECTS` and many distinct hosts (exactly the reproduction conditions above), nearly every connection handed to the shutdown queue immediately forces another queue entry to be force-terminated via `cshutdn_destroy_oldest()` → `Curl_cshutdn_terminate()`, **before its own graceful shutdown (TLS `close_notify` etc., started via `Curl_cshutdn_run_once`) has necessarily completed**.

My working hypothesis: forcing `Curl_cshutdn_terminate()` (and hence the new `discard_all`/`destroy()`-based close path) on a connection **while a lower-level filter's graceful shutdown is still in-flight** skips the final `socket_close()` in some interaction between the shutdown-in-progress state and the discard/destroy path — this is the piece I could not confirm without live tracing (gdb/strace on the actual process), so I'm flagging it as the most promising lead rather than a proven root cause.

## Environment

- curl/libcurl versions compared: 8.19.0-r0 vs 8.21.0-r0 (Alpine apk packages)
- OS: Alpine Linux 3.24.1 (identical base for both sides; only the curl/libcurl apk package version differed)
- TLS backend: OpenSSL (Alpine default)
- `CURLMOPT_MAXCONNECTS`: 5 (reproduction), also tested at 1000 (no leak)
- Multi API used: `curl_multi_socket_action` with `CURLMOPT_SOCKETFUNCTION`/`CURLMOPT_TIMERFUNCTION` (event-driven, `poll()`-based event loop in the reproducer)

## repro.c

```c
/* Multi-host curl_multi_socket_action reproducer: cycles requests across
 * many distinct hosts sharing ONE multi handle with a small connection
 * cache (CURLMOPT_MAXCONNECTS), mimicking a monitoring/poller-style
 * application that talks to many hosts through one shared multi handle.
 *
 * Usage: repro <base_url e.g. https://127.0.0.1:> <n_hosts>
 *              <close_host_count> <concurrency> <total_requests> <maxconnects>
 * close hosts are host indices [0, close_host_count) - sending
 * "Connection: close"; this parameter does not affect the leak (tested
 * both 0 and 2).
 */
#include <curl/curl.h>
#include <poll.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <unistd.h>

#define MAX_SOCKS 256

typedef struct {
    curl_socket_t fd;
    int action;
} tracked_sock_t;

static tracked_sock_t g_socks[MAX_SOCKS];
static int g_nsocks = 0;
static long g_timeout_ms = -1;

static size_t discard(void *ptr, size_t size, size_t nmemb, void *userdata) {
    (void)ptr; (void)userdata;
    return size * nmemb;
}

static int find_sock(curl_socket_t fd) {
    for (int i = 0; i < g_nsocks; i++) if (g_socks[i].fd == fd) return i;
    return -1;
}

static int sock_cb(CURL *easy, curl_socket_t s, int what, void *userp, void *socketp) {
    (void)easy; (void)userp; (void)socketp;
    int idx = find_sock(s);
    if (what == CURL_POLL_REMOVE) {
        if (idx >= 0) { g_socks[idx] = g_socks[g_nsocks - 1]; g_nsocks--; }
        return 0;
    }
    if (idx < 0) {
        if (g_nsocks >= MAX_SOCKS) return 0;
        idx = g_nsocks++;
        g_socks[idx].fd = s;
    }
    g_socks[idx].action = what;
    return 0;
}

static int timer_cb(CURLM *multi, long timeout_ms, void *userp) {
    (void)multi; (void)userp;
    g_timeout_ms = timeout_ms;
    return 0;
}

int g_n_hosts;
char g_host_url[MAX_SOCKS][128];

static void launch(CURLM *multi, CURL *easy, int host_idx) {
    curl_easy_setopt(easy, CURLOPT_URL, g_host_url[host_idx]);
    curl_easy_setopt(easy, CURLOPT_WRITEFUNCTION, discard);
    curl_easy_setopt(easy, CURLOPT_TIMEOUT, 5L);
    curl_easy_setopt(easy, CURLOPT_NOSIGNAL, 1L);
    curl_easy_setopt(easy, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 0L);
    curl_easy_setopt(easy, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST, 0L);
    curl_multi_add_handle(multi, easy);
}

typedef struct { CURL *easy; int host_idx; } slot_t;

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    if (argc < 7) {
        fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <base_url_no_port e.g. https://127.0.0.1:> <n_hosts> <close_host_count> <concurrency> <total_requests> <maxconnects>\n", argv[0]);
        return 2;
    }
    const char *base_url = argv[1];
    g_n_hosts = atoi(argv[2]);
    int close_hosts = atoi(argv[3]);
    int concurrency = atoi(argv[4]);
    int total = atoi(argv[5]);
    long maxconnects = atol(argv[6]);
    (void)close_hosts;

    for (int i = 0; i < g_n_hosts; i++) {
        snprintf(g_host_url[i], sizeof(g_host_url[i]), "%s%d/", base_url, 19100 + i);
    }

    curl_global_init(CURL_GLOBAL_DEFAULT);
    CURLM *multi = curl_multi_init();
    curl_multi_setopt(multi, CURLMOPT_SOCKETFUNCTION, sock_cb);
    curl_multi_setopt(multi, CURLMOPT_TIMERFUNCTION, timer_cb);
    curl_multi_setopt(multi, CURLMOPT_MAXCONNECTS, maxconnects);

    slot_t *slots = calloc(concurrency, sizeof(slot_t));
    srand(42);
    for (int i = 0; i < concurrency; i++) {
        slots[i].easy = curl_easy_init();
        slots[i].host_idx = rand() % g_n_hosts;
        launch(multi, slots[i].easy, slots[i].host_idx);
    }

    int still_running = 0;
    int completed = 0;
    curl_multi_socket_action(multi, CURL_SOCKET_TIMEOUT, 0, &still_running);

    struct pollfd pfds[MAX_SOCKS];
    while (completed < total) {
        int n = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < g_nsocks; i++) {
            pfds[n].fd = g_socks[i].fd;
            pfds[n].events = 0;
            if (g_socks[i].action == CURL_POLL_IN || g_socks[i].action == CURL_POLL_INOUT) pfds[n].events |= POLLIN;
            if (g_socks[i].action == CURL_POLL_OUT || g_socks[i].action == CURL_POLL_INOUT) pfds[n].events |= POLLOUT;
            n++;
        }
        int timeout = (g_timeout_ms < 0 || g_timeout_ms > 1000) ? 1000 : (int)g_timeout_ms;
        int rc = poll(n ? pfds : NULL, n, timeout);

        if (n == 0 || rc == 0) {
            curl_multi_socket_action(multi, CURL_SOCKET_TIMEOUT, 0, &still_running);
        } else {
            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                if (pfds[i].revents) {
                    int ev = 0;
                    if (pfds[i].revents & POLLIN) ev |= CURL_CSELECT_IN;
                    if (pfds[i].revents & POLLOUT) ev |= CURL_CSELECT_OUT;
                    if (pfds[i].revents & (POLLERR | POLLHUP)) ev |= CURL_CSELECT_ERR;
                    curl_multi_socket_action(multi, pfds[i].fd, ev, &still_running);
                }
            }
        }

        int msgq = 0;
        CURLMsg *msg;
        while ((msg = curl_multi_info_read(multi, &msgq)) != NULL) {
            if (msg->msg == CURLMSG_DONE) {
                CURL *done_easy = msg->easy_handle;
                completed++;
                curl_multi_remove_handle(multi, done_easy);
                int slot = -1;
                for (int i = 0; i < concurrency; i++) if (slots[i].easy == done_easy) { slot = i; break; }
                if (slot >= 0 && completed < total) {
                    slots[slot].host_idx = rand() % g_n_hosts;
                    launch(multi, done_easy, slots[slot].host_idx);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    fprintf(stdout, "done %d requests, concurrency=%d, hosts=%d, maxconnects=%ld, sleeping for inspection\n",
            total, concurrency, g_n_hosts, maxconnects);
    fflush(stdout);
    sleep(30);

    for (int i = 0; i < concurrency; i++) {
        curl_multi_remove_handle(multi, slots[i].easy);
        curl_easy_cleanup(slots[i].easy);
    }
    free(slots);
    curl_multi_cleanup(multi);
    curl_global_cleanup();
    return 0;
}
```

Mock HTTPS server used for testing (any equivalent works — the key properties are: TLS, and consistent handling of `Connection: close` vs keep-alive per host):

```python
#!/usr/bin/env python3
# spins up N HTTPS servers on 19100..19100+N-1; a configurable subset send
# "Connection: close", the rest keep-alive - only used to confirm the
# leak reproduces identically either way.
import http.server, socketserver, ssl, sys, os, threading

BASE_PORT = int(sys.argv[1]); N_HOSTS = int(sys.argv[2])
CLOSE_HOSTS = set(int(x) for x in sys.argv[3].split(","))

def make_handler(should_close):
    class Handler(http.server.BaseHTTPRequestHandler):
        protocol_version = "HTTP/1.1"
        def do_GET(self):
            body = b'{"data":{"ok":true}}'
            self.send_response(200)
            self.send_header("Content-Type", "application/json")
            self.send_header("Content-Length", str(len(body)))
            if should_close:
                self.send_header("Connection", "close")
            self.end_headers()
            self.wfile.write(body)
        def log_message(self, fmt, *args): pass
    return Handler

class Server(socketserver.ThreadingMixIn, socketserver.TCPServer):
    allow_reuse_address = True
    daemon_threads = True

def serve(idx):
    port = BASE_PORT + idx
    httpd = Server(("0.0.0.0", port), make_handler(idx in CLOSE_HOSTS))
    ctx = ssl.SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_TLS_SERVER)
    ctx.load_cert_chain(certfile="server.crt", keyfile="server.key")
    httpd.socket = ctx.wrap_socket(httpd.socket, server_side=True)
    httpd.serve_forever()

for i in range(N_HOSTS):
    threading.Thread(target=serve, args=(i,), daemon=True).start()
threading.Event().wait()
```

### I did this

Curl parses `<scheme>:///path` not as an empty authority section followed by a path, but as if the path were an authority.

My understanding (see below for motivation) is that this is correct in the case of the "special schemes" but not for other schemes.

Here's a repro in C, please forgive the machine-written code; I did edit it but I'm not much of a C writer. (Full bot disclaimer, this issue was discovered by me poking at `trurl` following discussions about the `at` protocol, not by a robot, but I did use the robot to help me in my investigation):

```c
#include <curl/curl.h>
#include <stdio.h>

static void show(const char *url, unsigned int flags) {
  CURLU *u = curl_url();
  char *scheme = NULL, *host = NULL, *port = NULL, *path = NULL;
  CURLUcode rc;

  printf("== %-40s (flags=0x%x)\n", url, flags);

  rc = curl_url_set(u, CURLUPART_URL, url, flags);
  if (rc) {
    printf("   curl_url_set rc=%d (%s)\n", rc, curl_url_strerror(rc));
    curl_url_cleanup(u);
    printf("\n");
    return;
  }

  curl_url_get(u, CURLUPART_SCHEME, &scheme, 0);
  curl_url_get(u, CURLUPART_HOST, &host, CURLU_GET_EMPTY);
  curl_url_get(u, CURLUPART_PORT, &port, 0);
  curl_url_get(u, CURLUPART_PATH, &path, 0);

  printf("   scheme=%s host=\"%s\" port=%s path=%s\n",
         scheme ? scheme : "(null)", host ? host : "(null)",
         port ? port : "(null)", path ? path : "(null)");

  curl_free(scheme);
  curl_free(host);
  curl_free(port);
  curl_free(path);
  curl_url_cleanup(u);
  printf("\n");
}

int main(void) {
  /* unknown scheme, trurl-style flags */
  unsigned int f = CURLU_NON_SUPPORT_SCHEME;

  printf("--- unknown scheme path is read as authority ---\n");
  show("at:///foo", f);
  // CURLU_NO_AUTHORITY doesn't change anything here
  show("at:///foo", f | CURLU_NO_AUTHORITY);
  show(
      "at:///did:plc:vwzwgnygau7ed7b7wt5ux7y2/app.bsky.feed.post/3k5nobkf2w72g",
      f);

  printf("--- HTTP parses the path as an authority ---\n");
  show("http:///foo.com/path", 0);

  return 0;
}
```

### I expected the following

I believe that per [RFC 3986](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc3986/#section-3.2), the authority section for `at:///path` ought properly to be considered empty, and `path` to be the path.

- Firefox and the `whatwg` [url parser tool](https://jsdom.github.io/whatwg-url/#url=YXQ6Ly8vZXhhbXBsZS5jb20v&base=YWJvdXQ6Ymxhbms=) both parse `https:///foo` as a hostname `foo`, which matches curl's behavior
    - I _think_ this is because of [special authority slashes state](https://url.spec.whatwg.org/#special-authority-slashes-state), which [applies to](https://url.spec.whatwg.org/#special-scheme) these url schemes: `ftp`, `file`, `http`, `https`, `ws`, and `wss` schemes, and nothing else
- Firefox and the `whatwg` parser both parse `at:///foo` as an empty hostname followed by the _path_ `/foo`
    - I think this is because the scheme is none of the above, so it does not enter "special authority slashes state"

So my expectation is the following:

- If the scheme of a URL of the form `scheme:///foo` is any of {`ftp`, `file`, `http`, `https`, `ws`, and `wss`}
    - curl already does the right thing, parsing `foo` as a hostname
- Else
    - curl ought to parse the URL with an empty hostname and a **path** of `/foo`

## Why does this matter?

The `at` protocol accidentally specified [invalid authority names](https://bnewbold.leaflet.pub/3mph4hzvbdc2v), and they're considering using an empty authority section in their `at` URLs to remediate the situation.

That's how I noticed this issue - I wondered how `trurl` would parse the proposed URLs with an empty authority, and found that it parsed them incorrectly; cf [the issue I filed there](https://github.com/curl/trurl/issues/443)

It seems to be a minor edge case, but one that would be worth fixing. I'd be happy to do the work to submit a PR if you thought it was worth fixing.

